

<html>
<head>
<title>Statistical Inference II Classnote</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=right><font size=-2>[Stat Inf II
classnotes, ISI, Kolkata]
</td></tr></table>
<h1>Optimality of SPRT</h1>




<h3>A Bayesian perspective</h3>

Consider testing a simple H<sub>0</sub> against a simple
H<sub>1</sub>. Given a (sequential) test, &phi;, we define 
&alpha;<sub>i</sub>(&phi;) as the probability of rejecting
H<sub>i</sub> when it is actually true. Denote by ASN<sub>i</sub>(&phi;) the
expected sample size of &phi; under H<sub>i</sub>.
Assume that we have the following.
<ul>
<li>Prior probability p
 of whether H<sub>0</sub> is true. Thus, 1-p is the prior probability
for H<sub>1</sub>.
<li>Losses W<sub>0</sub> and W<sub>1</sub>. We incur loss W<sub>i</sub> if
we reject H<sub>i</sub> when it is actually true.
<li>A cost c per sample (thus, to take a sample of size n, you have to pay
c*n) 
</ul>

So the expected risk in using a test &phi; is

<blockquote>
 R(p,&phi;)= p
              <img src="resources/statinf2/lbrace.gif"
              align=center>
              
                  &alpha;<sub>0</sub>(&phi;)W<sub>0</sub> + 
                  c*ASN<sub>0</sub>(&phi;)
                                          <img src="resources/statinf2/rbrace.gif"
                                          align=center>
                                          
                  +(1-p)
                        <img src="resources/statinf2/lbrace.gif"
                        align=center>
                        
                  &alpha;<sub>1</sub>(&phi;)W<sub>1</sub> + 
                  c*ASN<sub>1</sub>(&phi;)
                                          <img src="resources/statinf2/rbrace.gif"
                                          align=center>
                                          

</blockquote>

We want to minimise it. Note that R is a function of
many things: p, &phi;,W<sub>0</sub>,W<sub>1</sub> and c. However, in
the notation we have only shown the dependence of R on p and &phi;
explicitly. 

A test that mimimises this (if one exists) is called a Bayes test. We
shall now set out to find such a test. Observe first that this is
again a dynamic programming problem (DPP), much like the secretary
problem or minesweeper. At every step you have three choices: accept
H<sub>0</sub>, reject H<sub>0</sub> or continue sampling. The tree
is shown to the left.


<table align=left border=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td><img src="resources/statinf2/tl.gif"><td><td></tr>
<tr><td><td><img src="resources/statinf2/sprtree.gif"><td></tr>
<tr><td><td><td><img src="resources/statinf2/br.gif"></tr>
</table>


However, there is one important difference between this tree and those
of the secretary problem or minesweeper. Those were <i>finite</i>
trees, whereas this tree is infinite. Recall that for a finite tree
we could work backward starting from the leaf nodes. This expedient,
which we called
backward induction, is no more there for an
infinite tree. However, here we shall employ a neat, little trick.

<p>Suppose that we are at the root of the tree. We have three options:
accept without collecting any data, reject without collecting any
data, and collect one sample. In the first two cases, we have two
trivial tests. In either case the game stops
and so we can compute the expected risks.

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT6.1:</font></b> 
   
   Show that the two trivial tests have expected risks given by
   
   <blockquote>
   p W<sub>0</sub>   and   (1-p) W<sub>1</sub>.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

If, however, we choose to draw a sample, then the game continues and
we move to the next step, where we are faced with all possible
sequential tests that use at least one sample.

Define 

<blockquote>
R(p) = inf{R(p,&phi;): &phi; uses at least one sample}
</blockquote>

How do we know that the infimum exists? It is because, the set is
nonempty (there is at least one nontrivial test; in fact there are
many!) and the set is bounded from below by 0 (since risk is
nonnegative.) This R(p) is as yet unknown to us. 

<table align=right border=0 cellpadding=0>
<tr><td><img src="resources/statinf2/tl.gif"><td><td></tr>
<tr><td><td><img src="resources/statinf2/sprtloss.gif"><td></tr>
<tr><td><td><td><img src="resources/statinf2/br.gif"></tr>
</table>

However, we can
express the expected risk r(p) at the root in terms of
R(p):

<blockquote>
r(p) = min
          <img src="resources/statinf2/lbrace.gif"
          align=center>
          p W<sub>0</sub>,
                              R(p),
                              (1-p) W<sub>1</sub>
                                                 <img src="resources/statinf2/rbrace.gif"
                                                 align=center>
                                                 
</blockquote>

Consider the digram to the right to see why this is so.

Next let us explore R(p). 
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT6.2:</font></b> 
   
   Show that 
   
   <blockquote>
   c 
     <img src=
     "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
     align=top>
     
      R(p) 
           <img src=
           "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
           align=top>
           
            c+p W<sub>0</sub>.
   </blockquote>
   
   Hence conclude that R(0) = c and that R(p) is continuous at p=0.
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       
       Consider the non-trivial test based on a single observation that always
       rejects H<sub>0</sub>.
       ]
       </i>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT6.3:</font></b> 
   
   Show that R(p) is continuous at p=1, and that R(1)=c.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT6.4:</font></b> 
   
   Show that R(p) is concave, i.e., for any two points
   p<sub>1</sub>,p<sub>2</sub> in (0,1) and any a in [0,1],
   
   <blockquote>
   R(a*p<sub>1</sub> + (1-a)*p<sub>2</sub>) 
                                            <img src=
                                            "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                                            align=top>
                                            
                                             
   a*R(p<sub>1</sub>) + (1-a)*R(p<sub>2</sub>).
   
   </blockquote>
   
   Hence conclude that R(p) is continuous on (0,1).
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       For any &phi;, we have
       R(a*p<sub>1</sub> + (1-a)*p<sub>2</sub>, &phi;) =
       a*R(p<sub>1</sub>,&phi;) + (1-a)*R(p<sub>2</sub>,&phi;)
       ]
       </i>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

Combining the last three exercises we see that R(p) looks like the blue
line below. The red and green lines show the expected risks for the trivial
tests that do not collect any sample at all. Their minimum is r(p), as we
have already noted.


<p><center>
<img src="resources/statinf2/rp.gif">
</center><p>





<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT6.5:</font></b> 
   
   Show that if p 
                  <img src=
                  "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                  align=top>
                  
                   L, then the best strategy is to reject
   H<sub>0</sub>. Similarly, if p 
                                  <img src=
                                  "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                                  align=top>
                                  
                                   U, then the best strategy is to
   reject H<sub>0</sub>.  
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

Now suppose that p happens to lie between L and U. Then we have to
take one more sample. Now comes the trick. Since we have an infinite
tree this second stage is again essentially the same as the first
stage. We have the same W<sub>i</sub>'s and c. However, in light of
the single sample, x<sub>1</sub>, we have drawn, the prior p should be
updated to the 
posterior, which we shall call p(x<sub>1</sub>).

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT6.6:</font></b> 
   
   Compute p(x<sub>1</sub>) in terms of f<sub>i</sub>'s and x<sub>1</sub>.
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       
       You may like to use the following diagram, where f<sub>i</sub> is the
       density under H<sub>i</sub>.
       
       <p><center>
       <img src="resources/statinf2/post.gif">
       </center><p>
       
       ]
       </i>
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

Thus, if p(x) 
              <img src=
              "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
              align=top>
              
               L then the best strategy is to reject
H<sub>0</sub>, and if p(x) 
                           <img src=
                           "resources/statinf2/geq.png"
                           align=top>
                           
                            U, then you should accept it. If
p(x<sub>1</sub>) is inside (L,U), then you collect another sample,
x<sub>2</sub>, and look at p(x<sub>1</sub>,x<sub>2</sub>). 
<p>
In general, you keep on collecting data x<sub>i</sub>'s until
p(x<sub>1</sub>,x<sub>2</sub>,...) steps out of (L,U). Let n be the first
time 
p(x<sub>1</sub>,...,x<sub>n</sub>) goes out of (L,U). Then you accept
or 
reject H<sub>0</sub> according as p(x<sub>1</sub>,...,x<sub>n</sub>)

<img src=
"resources/statinf2/geq.png"
align=top>

 U or 
      <img src=
      "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
      align=top>
      
       L.
<p>
So you may be tempted to think that we can now carry out the Bayes
test. Wrong! We do not know L or U!!! We merely know that such cut off
points <i>exist</i> by continuity of the as yet unknown function
R(p). However, we have achieved one significant thing: we now know the
form of the Bayes test. This leads us to the following theorem.

<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Theorem:</b>
   
   The Bayes test is SPRT(A,B) for some suitable A,B.
   </td></tr></table>
   
<p>
   <table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
   <td>
   <b><i>Proof:</i></b> 
   
   <p>
      <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
      <td>
      <b><font color="#cc0000">
      Exercise SPRT6.7:</font></b> 
      
      Prove the theorem by expressing p(x<sub>1</sub>,...,x<sub>n</sub>) in
      terms of the likelihood ratio. 
      <br>
          <i>[Hint:
          
          You may consider taking
          
          <blockquote>
          A = p(1-U)/((1-p)U), and B = p(1-L)/((1-p)L).
          </blockquote>
          
          ]
          </i>
      
      </td></tr></table>
      </blockquote>
      
   
   <img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT6.8:</font></b> 
   
   Show that for any given A,B and p in (0,1) we can find
   W<sub>0</sub>,W<sub>1</sub> and c, such that SPRT(A,B) is the Bayes test.
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

Observe the fact that we still cannot compute either L,U or A,B
since R(p) is unknown. But still we are getting these results by
merely using the continuity of R(p). 


<h4>Optimality of SPRT</h4>

The above Bayesian optimality is not of much direct use, because we rarely
have explicit prior probabilities or quantifiable losses. However, it is
an important technical tool that will let us prove a more practical
optimality of SPRTs. 

<p>
   <table><tr><td bgcolor="#cccccc">
   <b>Theorem:</b>
   
   Suppose that &phi; is a SPRT, and &xi; is any other test. If 
   
   <blockquote>
   &alpha;<sub>i</sub>(&xi;)
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
   align=top>
   
   &alpha;<sub>i</sub>(&phi;) for both i=0,1,  
   </blockquote>
   
   then 
   
   <blockquote>
   ASN<sub>i</sub>(&phi;) 
                          <img src=
                          "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
                          align=top>
                          
                           ASN<sub>i</sub>(&xi;)
   for i=0,1.
   </blockquote>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   
<p>

<table><tr><td width=1 bgcolor="#cccccc"></td>
<td>
<b><i>Proof:</i></b> 

<p>
   <table><tr><td width=2 bgcolor="#cc0000"></td>
   <td>
   <b><font color="#cc0000">
   Exercise SPRT6.9:</font></b> 
   
   Show that for all p in (0,1) we have
   
   <blockquote>
   p ASN<sub>0</sub>(&phi;) + (1-p) ASN<sub>1</sub>(&phi;)
   
   <img src=
   "resources/statinf2/leq.png"
   align=top>
   
    
   p ASN<sub>0</sub>(&xi;) + (1-p) ASN<sub>1</sub>(&xi;)
   
   </blockquote>
    
   Hence complete the proof of the theorem.
   <br>
       <i>[Hint:
       
       Compare R(p,&phi;) and R(p,&xi;) for suitably chosen W<sub>i</sub>'s
       and c.
       ]
       </i>
   
   
   </td></tr></table>
   </blockquote>
   

<img src="resources/statinf2/square.gif">
</td></tr></table>
</blockquote>


